data.content:
# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it's completely removed
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — no abort/reset pattern exists
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime — your catch block is dead code

## Why `Thread.Abort()` Was Removed

It was always dangerous — it could fire *mid-write*, corrupt shared state, or interrupt `finally` blocks. .NET 8 enforces **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted cooperatively
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cooperative shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; no ResetAbort needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait for graceful shutdown with a hard timeout
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
            // You must ensure GetNextItemAsync actually observes the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. Blocking calls that ignore the token
```csharp
// BAD — this will hang forever after cancellation
var item = queue.Take(); // old blocking API, no token

// GOOD — interrupts immediately on cancel
var item = await queue.TakeAsync(token);
// or for sync APIs:
var item = queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T> supports this
```

If you wrap legacy blocking code, use a timeout loop:
```csharp
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    if (blockingCollection.TryTake(out var item, millisecondsTimeout: 500))
        return item;
}
throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
```

### 2. `volatile bool` is insufficient
The old `_running` flag can't interrupt a *blocked* `GetNextItem()` call. `CancellationToken` can — it wakes up async waits, semaphores, channels, etc.

### 3. Fire-and-forget `Task.Run` loses exceptions
```csharp
// BAD — exception silently swallowed
_workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token));
// Worker throws, nobody observes it

// GOOD — observe in StopAsync
await _workerTask; // surfaces any unhandled exception
```

### 4. No forced kill exists — design for cooperation
In .NET Framework you had a (dangerous) escape hatch. In .NET 8 you have **none**. Every blocking call in your pipeline *must* accept a `CancellationToken` or use a polling timeout. Audit every call in `GetNextItem()` and `ProcessItem()`.

### 5. Consider `BackgroundService` if hosted
If this runs inside ASP.NET Core or a Generic Host app, inherit from `BackgroundService` instead — it wires up lifetime and cancellation automatically:
```csharp
public class Processor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        // same loop, token provided by the host
    }
}
```

### Migration Checklist

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread` + `IsBackground` | `Task.Run` or `BackgroundService` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove — not needed |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(N)` | `await Task.Delay(N, token)` |
